<TEXT>     Industry officials released a downbeat report as the 10-day trade
exposition opened.;    Many companies appeared to be taking a more
conservative approach as they presented new lines, sticking with ideas that
worked well in 1990. That meant more baby dolls for girls, wrestling action
figures for boys and games and toys spun off from TV shows and comic books.;  
 The Toy Manufacturers of America, the trade group that sponsors the big show,
said sales of traditional toys -- those other than video games -- were
virtually unchanged last year. Shipments rose just 0.3 percent in terms of
dollars and 0.2 percent in terms of units.;    The group estimated video game
sales rose 20.9 percent in dollars and 33.8 percent in units.;    Officials
forecast wholesale and retail toy sales would rise 5 percent for 1991, but
they said as much as two-thirds of that increase would be from price
